Once in a great while a book comes along that changes the way we see the world and helps to fuel a nationwide social movement. The New Jim Crow is such a book. Praised by Harvard Law professor Lani Guinier as &quot;brave and bold,&quot; this book directly challenges the notion that the election of Barack Obama signals a new era of colorblindness. With dazzling candor, legal scholar Michelle Alexander argues that &quot;we have not ended racial caste in America; we have merely redesigned it.&quot; By targeting black men through the War on Drugs and decimating communities of color, the U.S. criminal justice system functions as a contemporary system of racial controlÃ¢â‚¬â€relegating millions to a permanent second-class statusÃ¢â‚¬â€even as it formally adheres to the principle of colorblindness. In the words of Benjamin Todd Jealous, president and CEO of the NAACP, this book is a &quot;call to action.&quot;

Called &quot;stunning&quot; by Pulitzer PrizeÃ¢â‚¬â€œwinning historian David Levering Lewis, &quot;invaluable&quot; by the Daily Kos, &quot;explosive&quot; by Kirkus, and &quot;profoundly necessary&quot; by the Miami Herald, this updated and revised paperback edition of The New Jim Crow, now with a foreword by Cornel West, is a must-read for all people of conscience.



